Below is a **complete, self‑contained binding** for the (fictional) C++ class  

```cpp
namespace pcapng {
    struct frame {
        uint64_t   ts;          // timestamp, nanoseconds since epoch
        const uint8_t *data;    // pointer to the raw packet bytes
        size_t        len;      // length of the packet
    };

    // An iterator that walks a file – it is cheap to copy, cheap to
    // compare to the “end” iterator and has the usual ++ / * operators.
    class iterator {
    public:
        iterator();                     // creates the “end” iterator
        iterator(const char *filename); // opens a file and points to the first frame
        bool   operator!=(const iterator&) const;
        iterator& operator++();          // advance to the next frame
        const frame& operator*() const;  // current frame (valid only if not equal to end())
    };
}
```

The binding is deliberately **minimal** – it only exposes what the OCaml side needs
(and nothing more).  The hot path is the `iter` function that walks the whole
collection while calling back an OCaml closure for each frame.  The implementation
keeps the loop in C++ so that we pay only the cost of building a *single* OCaml
value per frame and of invoking the callback.

---

## 1. The OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`)

```ocaml
(* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng.mli – public OCaml interface
   ---------------------------------------------------------------------- *)

(** A handle to a pcapng file.  The value is opaque; it is created by
    {!open_file} and must be closed with {!close}. *)
type t

(** A single captured frame.  The fields are deliberately simple so that
    the generated code can be inlined by the OCaml optimiser. *)
type frame = {
  timestamp : int64;   (** nanoseconds since the Unix epoch *)
  data      : bytes;   (** raw packet bytes – a fresh copy for each frame *)
}

(** Raised by {!next_opt} when the iterator is exhausted. *)
exception End_of_file

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises [Sys_error] if the file cannot
    be opened. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Close a handle.  After this call the handle must not be used again. *)
val close : t -> unit

(** Iterate over the whole file, invoking the supplied closure for every
    frame.  The loop runs in C++ – the only allocation per frame is the
    OCaml record that is handed to the callback.  If the callback raises,
    the exception propagates to the caller and the iteration stops
    immediately.

    The function is deliberately *not* tail‑recursive: the recursion lives
    in C++ and therefore does not consume OCaml stack space. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** A one‑shot version that returns the next frame as an [option].  It is
    useful for “pull‑based” programming, but it is *much* slower than
    {!iter} because it allocates a temporary OCaml value for each call. *)
val next_opt : t -> frame option
```

